{<b>Regarding Partner</b>

<b>Bidding.</b> West opens 1\D. North's 1NT overcall shows much the same as a 1NT
opening bid, but also with some strength in opener's suit.

East passes. South holds 10 points, giving her side at least 25 points, making
3NT a good proposition.

<b>Defense.</b> It is unlikely that East can set up and run hearts given that there
are no outside entries. East chooses to lead partner's suit, and starts with
the \D9, highest of a doubleton.

<i>Fine point. </i>West can afford to overtake the \D9 opening lead in case East
started with a singleton.

<b>Declarer play.</b> You (North) count six sure tricks and need three more. A finesse
of the \HJ might get you one more, but that's not enough. You will need to
promote three tricks in clubs.

You should hold up in diamonds in case diamonds are 5-2 or 6-1 and East holds
the \CA or \CK.

Unfortunately for you, if East leads diamonds and the defenders continue
diamonds at every opportunity, the defense will take three diamond and two club
tricks. Had diamonds not been led, or if diamonds had divided 4-3, or if East
held the \CA or \CK, then you would have made 3NT.

<b>Key point.</b> The diamonds offer the best chance of defeating the contract, but
the defenders have to be persistent. The first step is for East to lead
diamonds, the suit East's partner bid. Then, West has to continue leading
diamonds at every opportunity in order to defeat declarer’s contract. Notrump
contracts are often a race to see which side can develop sufficient winners
first.}
