{<b>In Good Order</b>

<b>Bidding.</b> East passes. South holds a balanced hand of 15 points, and opens 1NT,
though some might find a 1\D opening bid more to their taste.

West passes. North holds the values for game (but not slam), but would prefer
to play in spades if South also holds four. North uses the Stayman 2\C
convention to see if South holds four spades.

East passes. South bids 2\D to deny holding a four-card major.

West passes. North proceeds to the game in notrump since there is no fit in
spades.

<i>Alternate bidding. </i>If South judges the hand as not strong enough to open 1NT,
the auction would be:

     1\D-1\S; 1NT-3NT; All pass

<b>Defense.</b> Hearts is West's best suit. On the \HJ opening lead (highest of
interior sequence), East realizes that South holds the \HQ. She plays the \HA
in case partner holds the \HK, which avoids presenting declarer with an
undeserved trick with the \HQ. East returns the \H2 as a count signal so that
West will know that East started with an even number of hearts (and now has an
odd number remaining). The recommended auction also revealed that South does
not hold four hearts.

<b>Declarer play. </b>The defenders must immediately take their four heart tricks and
the \CA to defeat 3NT. Otherwise declarer takes nine tricks — four spades and
five diamonds.

<b>Key point.</b> Leading the highest card from a strong sequence often provides the
defenders with a good chance to defeat the contract. If partner leads a high
card, you have to use your imagination to visualize partner’s holding in the
suit. In this deal, East knew from West’s opening lead that declarer held the
\HQ. If partner held the \HK, then declarer’s \HQ could be trapped — if East
won the first trick with the \HA.}
