{<b>Bidding.</b> West passes. North holds a balanced hand of 22 points. North
starts with an opening bid of 2\C to show at least 22 points of any
distribution.

East passes. South must respond to a 2\C opening bid. With less than eight
points, South responds 2\D, an artificial “waiting” bid.

West passes. North rebids 2NT to show a balanced hand of 22–24 points.

East passes. South knows there are enough points for game, but not slam. With
no interest in a major-suit contract, South bids 3NT to end the auction.

<b>Defense.</b> Without a sequence, East leads \H6 (fourth-best). West cannot
contribute to winning the trick, so plays the \H7 as a count signal.

<b>Declarer play.</b> You count seven sure winners, plus a heart trick from the
opening lead. You will need to get a trick from clubs.

<i>Fine point. </i>Declarer's best line is to win the opening lead with the
\H10 and immediately lead the \C2 (or tricky \CJ) <u>from dummy</u> since there
will have nine tricks if West ducks (East will never duck the \CA if looking
at the setting tricks in hearts). West must realize that East can have at
most seven points, and that the \HK Q and \CQ will not be enough to defeat the
contract. Only the \HA K x x x will suffice to defeat the contract, so West
should play for that holding by winning the \CA and returning a heart.

Of course, this is a difficult defense to envision. Another winning view is
that West must win the \CA immediately and lead hearts in order to preserve
any later entry East may have.

If declarer plays winners immediately, West will need to keep her second heart
so that she can play it after winning the \CA.

<b>Key point.</b> The only way for the defenders to defeat the contract is for
East to lead a low heart. Declarer takes the first trick, but when West gets
the lead with the \CA, West leads a heart. East has enough winners to defeat
the contract. Notice that West should return partner’s suit even when declarer
or dummy wins the first trick. Also notice that West must rise with the \CA at
the first opportunity — otherwise, declarer has nine winners (four diamonds,
three spades, one heart and one club) for game.}
