{<b>A Little Help</b>

<b>Bidding.</b> East passes. South holds a balanced hand of 15 points, and
opens 1NT, though some might find a 1\D opening bid more to their taste.

West passes. North holds enough points for game, but not slam. North would
prefer to play in a major-suit fit, if one exists, so bids the Stayman 2\C
convention.

East passes. South bids 2\D to deny holding a four-card major suit.

West passes. North places the contract in 3NT, assured that there is no fit in
a major suit.

<b>Defense.</b> West leads the \C2 as less is needed from partner in clubs to
develop tricks than in hearts or diamonds. Besides, the \HA and \DA will be
entries to established clubs, but not the reverse.

<i>Fine point. </i>East should play \C9 if declarer ducks the opening lead in
dummy, but it doesn't matter here. We will look more closely at surrounding
dummy's honors in the class about <i>third-hand play<b>.</b></i>

If declarer holds up the \CA, East continues with a low club as a count signal
to show that she remains with an odd number of clubs.

<b>Declarer play.</b> You count five sure tricks and need four more. You should
play on diamonds, rather than hearts, as diamonds alone will provide enough
extra tricks for the contract.

West can take her club tricks and the \HA once she wins the \DA. If East is
going to win the fourth club, then West should cash the \HA before giving up
the lead.

<b>Key point.</b> West has a choice of three suits that would be reasonable to
lead. If North opens 1\D rather than 1NT, West can eavesdrop on the opponent's
bidding, making the better unbid suit the logical choice for an opening lead.
If North opens 1NT, West will have less information to guide her opening lead,
and must reason well to find the club lead. If West leads any other suit,
declarer will have no trouble making the contract.}
